[Guest 1]: I did like some of the most awesome stuff, some of the most. So, oh, as I say, in Bombay,

00:05:10.080 --> 00:05:17.040
[Guest 1]: I had a long struggle and I went through what are called bhajan videos and I won a beauty

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:21.800
[Guest 1]: pageant in Bombay in my day. So yeah, so eventually after that, I sort of moved on. I ended up

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:25.440
[Guest 1]: going and studying IR. And when I started international relations, it just sort of switched.

00:05:25.440 --> 00:05:29.760
[Guest 1]: I moved to journalism as opposed to foreign policy per se, but my interest was foreign

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:33.600
[Guest 1]: policy reportage. There was very little done in India and particularly at the grade where

00:05:33.600 --> 00:05:39.400
[Guest 1]: I started. It took a few years once I finally went to China and I worked over there and

00:05:39.400 --> 00:05:44.000
[Guest 1]: I came back from there. And that's when sort of the career in foreign policy, you know,

00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:49.560
[Guest 1]: studying China sort of evolved. So that's say the last five, six years when that sort

00:05:49.560 --> 00:05:53.840
[Guest 1]: of evolved. But that's the trajectory. I went through years of journalism, about 12 years,

00:05:53.840 --> 00:05:57.320
[Guest 1]: most of some of them in India, three of them in China, and then subsequently moved out

00:05:57.320 --> 00:06:02.040
[Guest 1]: of journalism because it just became a place from which I needed refuge. And therefore

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:04.760
[Guest 1]: I moved to research in foreign policy, particularly because that was my interest.

00:06:04.760 --> 00:06:08.840
[Amit Varma]: And to outsiders, it seems like a very dry subject. It's almost like the grass is green

00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:12.240
[Amit Varma]: on the other side in this context. But you know, when I speak to both of you, I get the

00:06:12.240 --> 00:06:17.080
[Amit Varma]: sense that you really love your jobs. You really love foreign policy. Yeah. So did you

00:06:17.080 --> 00:06:21.800
[Amit Varma]: wake up in the morning and look forward to figuring out how the dynamic changed today?

00:06:21.800 --> 00:06:27.080
[Guest 2]: No, it's just things keep happening, right? They never let you, your guard is never down

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:30.880
[Guest 2]: because something or the other is happening. So you just figure out and learn something

00:06:30.880 --> 00:06:34.960
[Guest 1]: new. Also, I think, you know, at a certain level, and I think this doesn't operate very

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:39.240
[Guest 1]: consciously, but for me, at least at a subconscious level, foreign policy was always sort of one

00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:44.160
[Guest 1]: step above covering domestic stuff. It always felt like, maybe it felt like, you know, that

00:06:44.160 --> 00:06:49.880
[Guest 1]: is much more cooler. But it also, I guess, has to do with the fact that, you know, when

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:53.200
[Guest 1]: you go back to studying foreign policy, just the importance that Nehru gave to foreign

00:06:53.200 --> 00:06:56.680
[Guest 1]: policy, I think that sort of also has a sense that, you know, okay, no, this is a bigger

00:06:56.680 --> 00:07:00.720
[Guest 1]: deal to cover. If you're really smart, you're a strategist, you do all of this. If you're

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:04.280
[Guest 1]: a steezy politician, you do domestic stuff. So that's the sort of stuff that I think pays

00:07:04.280 --> 00:07:08.480
[Guest 2]: subconsciously. Yeah, no, that's a good point. Because I've heard that earlier as well. Because

00:07:08.480 --> 00:07:14.240
[Guest 2]: when you discuss foreign policy, it allows you to escape in a sense from what happens

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:19.140
[Guest 2]: in the domestic policy. So it's almost an admission that things can't change locally.

00:07:19.140 --> 00:07:24.360
[Guest 2]: So let's think of a step above. But generally, our work because we deal with public policy,

00:07:24.360 --> 00:07:27.520
[Guest 2]: it straddles both and there is not much distinction.

00:07:27.520 --> 00:07:32.000
[Amit Varma]: Controversial question. Is it simpler than say something like macroeconomics? Because

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:35.600
[Amit Varma]: I guess someone who's into macroeconomics is dealing with like millions of variables

00:07:35.600 --> 00:07:39.600
[Amit Varma]: and everything is up in the air and it almost feels like they're winging it at times. Whereas

00:07:39.600 --> 00:07:45.520
[Amit Varma]: for you guys, okay, it's more or less a zero sum game. And it's a few players. And actually,

00:07:45.520 --> 00:07:52.200
[Guest 2]: no, I would say both of them are equally similar that both of them are voodoo many times. Because

00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:57.520
[Guest 2]: in macroeconomics, unlike in microeconomics, you know, right in macroeconomics, for everything

00:07:57.520 --> 00:08:02.320
[Guest 2]: you can give a justification. Yeah, right. Similarly, in foreign policy, also, it's the

00:08:02.320 --> 00:08:07.800
[Guest 2]: same. Yes, people can justify anything. And there is very little of outcome irrelevant

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:12.760
[Guest 2]: learning. So like, if you learn something which happens goes against your belief, that

00:08:12.760 --> 00:08:17.880
[Guest 2]: updation of your Bayesian priors happens very less in foreign policy as well, you will just

00:08:17.880 --> 00:08:23.520
[Guest 2]: justify Oh, yeah, this thing had to happen. Yeah, Taliban went away from Afghanistan,

00:08:23.520 --> 00:08:28.720
[Guest 2]: I knew it would happen. You know, this US went away, Russia had come in in 79, then

00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:33.280
[Guest 2]: the US came due to balance of power changing, they went away. So there is a lot of such

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:37.680
[Guest 2]: things which happen in like in microeconomics and foreign policy as well. And I think one

00:08:37.680 --> 00:08:41.320
[Guest 1]: of the reasons is that, you know, there is so much of foreign policy that links to domestic

00:08:41.320 --> 00:08:44.720
[Guest 1]: politics and policies in other countries, that there are so many other variables and

00:08:44.720 --> 00:08:48.280
[Guest 1]: you don't account for when you're basically looking at the state as one entity without

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:51.720
[Guest 1]: looking at the internal dynamics, which is something that a lot of people end up doing.

00:08:51.720 --> 00:08:55.280
[Guest 1]: And that's where it becomes far more complicated. So yeah, what he said, I have a good example

00:08:55.280 --> 00:08:59.760
[Guest 2]: for that, like, for example, whenever you're trying to analyse decision making of a government,

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:03.280
[Guest 2]: what type of models will you apply, right? The basic one which will apply is rational

00:09:03.280 --> 00:09:09.280
[Guest 2]: actor model. So you'll treat the state as one unitary actor, which does things in certain

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:13.480
[Guest 2]: ways. And but that obviously is not the right model, right? You will have to understand

00:09:13.480 --> 00:09:18.600
[Guest 2]: better models. So there are bargaining models, or there are models which look at bureaucratic

00:09:18.600 --> 00:09:23.360
[Guest 2]: actor models, which look at how institutions within that state perform, right? But what

00:09:23.360 --> 00:09:27.760
[Guest 2]: happens often in foreign policies, because we don't know much about the other state,

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:32.960
[Guest 2]: we try to analyse it as a rational actor model. So we can explain anything that China does,

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:37.440
[Guest 2]: for example, through this rational actor model, okay, China is doing something in Sri Lanka,

00:09:37.440 --> 00:09:43.960
[Guest 2]: because you know, this is this, yeah, you know, it is very, that every action is calculated

00:09:43.960 --> 00:09:49.840
[Guest 2]: as a result of something which is pursued by one actor in this state, which is not true,

00:09:49.840 --> 00:09:54.320
[Guest 2]: right? Even in a party state like China, there will be multiple actors who are having their

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:59.320
[Guest 2]: own interests. So in foreign policy, also, we start off with a rational actor model.

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:04.360
[Guest 2]: But a great analysis only comes if you are able to improve that rational actor model

00:10:04.360 --> 00:10:10.040
[Guest 2]: with other layers of analysis, like bureaucratic actor or bargaining. In fact, I'm reminded

00:10:10.040 --> 00:10:13.840
[Amit Varma]: of an episode I did in the Bangladesh war with Srinath Raghavan. And a substantial part

00:10:13.840 --> 00:10:17.840
[Amit Varma]: of that was about how the US was functioning at that time, where they were acting completely

00:10:17.840 --> 00:10:21.760
[Amit Varma]: incoherently, because Nixon and Kissinger believed one thing and the State Department

00:10:21.760 --> 00:10:26.440
[Amit Varma]: believed another thing. And there was a constant conflict between these. And obviously, these

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:31.200
[Amit Varma]: are only sort of two points. But you know, you might think you're acting with a single

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:34.480
[Amit Varma]: state which will act rationally, but acting with many different actors who have their

00:10:34.480 --> 00:10:40.120
[Amit Varma]: own interests and incentives. And speaking of incentives, you know, because in your role

00:10:40.120 --> 00:10:46.800
[Amit Varma]: as foreign policy analyst, you are expected to explain the world, is there then an incentive

00:10:46.800 --> 00:10:51.680
[Amit Varma]: to simplify and create simplistic narratives, because the world in many ways is incredibly

00:10:51.680 --> 00:10:57.840
[Amit Varma]: complex, you know, and not always so easy to explain, but people want bad explanations.

00:10:57.840 --> 00:11:02.480
[Guest 1]: I mean, I think there is, there is an incentive to do that. And there is a there's also a

00:11:02.480 --> 00:11:05.600
[Guest 1]: desire to do that, because it's easier to communicate that way. And therefore, you end

00:11:05.600 --> 00:11:08.920
[Guest 1]: up getting stuck with some of these labels. So for example, if you look at what Chinese

00:11:08.920 --> 00:11:12.480
[Guest 1]: have been doing with Belt and Road, the narrative of Oh, this is debt wrap, this is well thought

00:11:12.480 --> 00:11:16.440
[Guest 1]: out imposing debt on other people to take over their sovereignty or their assets. It's

00:11:16.440 --> 00:11:19.520
[Guest 1]: one of the simplistic narratives which has gotten hold. And as much as now you try to

00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:23.200
[Guest 1]: sort of break that saying that look, it's not necessarily that's how that's not necessarily

00:11:23.200 --> 00:11:26.960
[Guest 1]: how it's functioning. There are so many other complications involved. It's not easily bought.

00:11:26.960 --> 00:11:29.720
[Guest 1]: I mean, from an analyst point of view, yes, there is an incentive to do that, because

00:11:29.720 --> 00:11:33.640
[Guest 1]: that's your instant claim to a headline. But if that's what you desire, then you should

00:11:33.640 --> 00:11:37.280
[Guest 1]: be doing that. But if that's not what you desire, and you want to get sort of below

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:40.680
[Guest 1]: the sort of surface of things, and I think it's, you know, I think that's the eventual

00:11:40.680 --> 00:11:46.400
[Guest 1]: sort of bit that will get valued, the newspaper headline will go away within less than 24

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:50.480
[Guest 1]: hours insight, which is valuable sustains over a period of time. So as an analyst, that's

00:11:50.480 --> 00:11:53.600
[Guest 1]: the choice that you end up having to make, you know, what is it that you want to do?

00:11:53.600 --> 00:11:56.680
[Guest 1]: And I think that's why so that there exists an incentive. But there is this, I think,

00:11:56.680 --> 00:12:00.280
[Guest 1]: for somebody who wants to understand the world, if you're going in it to try and understand

00:12:00.280 --> 00:12:03.600
[Guest 1]: the world, I think or try and understand how foreign policy operates, you want to sort

00:12:03.600 --> 00:12:07.600
[Guest 2]: of step back and take a look at things better. I don't think it's very different amid compared

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:13.480
[Guest 2]: to any other discipline. For example, in economics as well, we'll always try to simplify reality

00:12:13.480 --> 00:12:19.320
[Guest 2]: and model reality because you want to rational actor itself in economics is a very big concept,

00:12:19.320 --> 00:12:24.840
[Guest 2]: right? You because by making that assumption, you are able to then see outside that individual

00:12:24.840 --> 00:12:29.320
[Guest 2]: otherwise, you will then be stuck with why is the individual doing right. So simplifying

00:12:29.320 --> 00:12:34.820
[Guest 2]: reality and building models is the first step, right? That's how you build on to your understanding

00:12:34.820 --> 00:12:38.760
[Guest 2]: of the world. So I think foreign policy is something similar. So you build up models

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:43.320
[Guest 2]: to understand the world in better ways, you will simplify things. And the hope is that

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:48.440
[Guest 2]: you will then apply nuance it as you understand it. But I think the difference between building

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:53.120
[Guest 1]: a theoretical model, which explains certain consequences and actions is different as opposed

00:12:53.120 --> 00:12:58.280
[Guest 1]: to simplifying reality. A theoretical model will help you evaluate or filter through realistic

00:12:58.280 --> 00:13:01.640
[Guest 1]: events to try and say, well, these are probably the underlying causes. And these are probably

00:13:01.640 --> 00:13:05.820
[Guest 1]: the underlying motivations, whereas actually creating a narrative to simplify what could

00:13:05.820 --> 00:13:09.320
[Guest 1]: be very complex actions don't necessarily survive. A theoretical model will survive.

00:13:09.320 --> 00:13:12.240
[Guest 1]: I mean, things like in foreign policy, new realism and all will survive, but they will

00:13:12.240 --> 00:13:15.560
[Guest 1]: get updated. But the theoretical base of the model will survive because it gives you one

00:13:15.560 --> 00:13:20.400
[Guest 1]: way of looking at the world. Whereas when narratives are created, say, for example,

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:24.840
[Guest 1]: the US's role in the Middle East is predominantly oil driven by the big mafia, whatever, by

00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:28.000
[Guest 1]: the big oil lobbies, those are the narratives sustain themselves, but they might not necessarily

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:32.160
[Guest 1]: explain foreign policy in itself. Whereas a model such as realism as an approach to

00:13:32.160 --> 00:13:35.440
[Guest 1]: things might be able to explain to you largely why certain actions are happening and why

00:13:35.440 --> 00:13:39.720
[Amit Varma]: states behave in a certain way. In fact, you know, the pundit economy, so to say, the talking

00:13:39.720 --> 00:13:44.120
[Amit Varma]: heads on TV and all of that, they have to exude certainty and therefore they have to

00:13:44.120 --> 00:13:47.160
[Amit Varma]: simplify and this happened because of this and blah, blah, blah. And there's no space

00:13:47.160 --> 00:13:51.840
[Amit Varma]: for nuance. But however, when you're analyzing something, have you guys internalized probabilistic

00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:57.720
[Amit Varma]: thinking and how hard or easy is that? And you know, how difficult is it to avoid the

00:13:57.720 --> 00:14:01.320
[Amit Varma]: temptation of giving into that and just coming to a conclusion about something and moving

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:05.400
[Guest 2]: on? Yeah. So I don't think we have done a lot of

00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:09.800
[Guest 2]: work on, say, probabilistic thinking because you need a lot of data to be able to also

00:14:09.800 --> 00:14:14.480
[Guest 2]: use some of these things. But when we talk about interstate relations, you don't have

00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:20.760
[Guest 2]: that much available. But so, for example, when we try to talk about things, we try to

00:14:20.760 --> 00:14:26.400
[Guest 2]: avoid certainty and certitude and the ignorance that comes with certitude we try to avoid.

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:31.000
[Guest 2]: So we try to say even when we are predicting things, we would like to say that, you know,

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:35.120
[Guest 2]: these are things which are likely based on our understanding of the world and the model

00:14:35.120 --> 00:14:39.320
[Guest 2]: that we have developed. If things go awry, then we have to update our model. That's how

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:42.240
[Guest 1]: we think about it. Yeah. And sort of a tangent to that is I was

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:47.240
[Guest 1]: recently in a Twitter discussion with somebody and we were talking about some events, controversial

00:14:47.240 --> 00:14:51.800
[Guest 1]: stuff related to China. And the answer that I got was, well, if your answer is that it's

00:14:51.800 --> 00:14:55.840
[Guest 1]: complex and that's not good enough, you need to have a certain clarity about it. And I

00:14:55.840 --> 00:14:58.920
[Guest 1]: was like, but it is complex. And what are you supposed to do about that? So I think

00:14:58.920 --> 00:15:01.540
[Guest 1]: there is like this sort of ties into what you asked earlier, right? There is a pressure

00:15:01.540 --> 00:15:05.120
[Guest 1]: to be certain about certain things. But yeah, and the best that you can do is you can create

00:15:05.120 --> 00:15:10.000
[Guest 1]: a model and if your model sustains the test of time, that's when you know you've probably

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:13.160
[Amit Varma]: done well. Let's move from certainty to clarity, right?

00:15:13.160 --> 00:15:17.360
[Amit Varma]: Now models that you describe, frames through which you view the world in any field, useful

00:15:17.360 --> 00:15:20.840
[Amit Varma]: because then they give clarity to the way you look at the world. And of course, if the

00:15:20.840 --> 00:15:24.680
[Amit Varma]: frame is wrong, then your clarity could be misconceived clarity. But nevertheless, frames

00:15:24.680 --> 00:15:29.320
[Amit Varma]: are extremely useful. So what kind of frames do you have, for example, ask each of you

00:15:29.320 --> 00:15:33.280
[Amit Varma]: this to look at sort of the world, foreign policy, international relations?

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:38.760
[Guest 2]: Yeah. So this is like talking about all the models that exist in IR, but international

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:43.520
[Guest 2]: relations discipline itself has some theories, right? Like, so there will be a theory of

00:15:43.520 --> 00:15:48.680
[Guest 2]: realism. So the realism theory says that the most important determinant of anything that

00:15:48.680 --> 00:15:53.760
[Guest 2]: happens in the world is power. So it's about who has more power, the Matsya Naya thing,

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:58.560
[Guest 2]: which even the cotillion things, right? Big fish eats small fish. So you have to be the

00:15:58.560 --> 00:16:03.120
[Guest 2]: big fish. If you are a small fish, you have to ally with other small fish or big fish

00:16:03.120 --> 00:16:06.040
[Guest 2]: to in order to resist a big fish from eating.

00:16:06.040 --> 00:16:07.040
[Amit Varma]: And that's a zero-sum view.

00:16:07.040 --> 00:16:13.040
[Guest 2]: Yeah, yeah. So foreign policy is seen in terms of this balancing and bandwagoning. So that

00:16:13.040 --> 00:16:17.880
[Guest 2]: is realism. And there are other frames as well. There was a liberalism school of international

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:23.200
[Guest 2]: relations also, which said that, you know, that this is not true. Ultimately, the goal

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:30.040
[Guest 2]: of all foreign policy should be to increase liberal values. And as economies get intertwined

00:16:30.040 --> 00:16:34.680
[Guest 2]: with each other, certain kinds of values will become more popular than others. That school

00:16:34.680 --> 00:16:40.720
[Guest 2]: was discredited with what things are happening now, right? So and then there were other constructivism

00:16:40.720 --> 00:16:45.800
[Guest 2]: that was another view, which said that it's not necessarily that states are always going

00:16:45.800 --> 00:16:50.840
[Guest 2]: to act like this. The ultimate decisions by states are shaped by the individuals there.

00:16:50.840 --> 00:16:55.560
[Guest 2]: So as long as you can influence elite opinion in different countries, you might actually

00:16:55.560 --> 00:17:01.240
[Guest 2]: achieve different outcomes. These are like three broad schools of international relations.

00:17:01.240 --> 00:17:08.000
[Guest 2]: Now, when I look at it, apart from these things, let's look at India, right? Indian foreign

00:17:08.000 --> 00:17:13.680
[Guest 2]: policy, the frame that we use for looking at foreign policy, the objective that we want

00:17:13.680 --> 00:17:19.400
[Guest 2]: to think about is, is any action that we do in foreign policy, is it leading to the yoga

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:25.000
[Guest 2]: kshema of Indians? Which is, is it bringing, yoga kshema means peaceful enjoyment of prosperity.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:30.400
[Guest 2]: So is that leading us to more yoga kshema or not? If it is not, it is a bad foreign

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:35.720
[Guest 2]: policy. If it is, it is going in the right direction. So, you know, we look at that.

00:17:35.720 --> 00:17:40.240
[Guest 2]: So for example, let me give you an example where it might be controversial. So many people

00:17:40.240 --> 00:17:45.800
[Guest 2]: say, think that territorial sovereignty or territorial integrity rather is the most important

00:17:45.800 --> 00:17:52.160
[Guest 2]: idea of any nation state. So the view that we come from is, it's not true to say that,

00:17:52.160 --> 00:17:56.960
[Guest 2]: you know, if yoga kshema is central to our view, there might be certain cases where you

00:17:56.960 --> 00:18:02.280
[Guest 2]: might want to give away some territory in exchange of prosperity of more Indians. And

00:18:02.280 --> 00:18:06.360
[Guest 2]: in fact, there exists a realistic case of that where India exchanged some land with

00:18:06.360 --> 00:18:10.240
[Guest 2]: Bangladesh because there are these second order enclaves. Within Bangladesh, there is

00:18:10.240 --> 00:18:15.160
[Guest 2]: India and within India, there are Bangladesh. So, and those people had, they were almost

00:18:15.160 --> 00:18:19.040
[Guest 2]: stateless. They couldn't have any services of Indians and Bangladeshis couldn't have

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:25.600
[Guest 2]: services either. So we exchanged those lands. We, in fact, gave away more land than we got

00:18:25.600 --> 00:18:32.200
[Guest 2]: in return, but that now there is consistency. Those people can have a much better life than

00:18:32.200 --> 00:18:36.880
[Amit Varma]: they had earlier. So it is good for us. So yoga kshema is basically what Thomas Jefferson

00:18:36.880 --> 00:18:43.360
[Guest 2]: would call the pursuit of happiness. Peaceful enjoyment of prosperity. Peaceful enjoyment.

00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:47.760
[Amit Varma]: So peace is also important. Yeah, the means. So the means, you have the means in the end

00:18:47.760 --> 00:18:51.680
[Amit Varma]: right there. So when you kind of think of the world, you'd once written essay for Pragati

00:18:51.680 --> 00:18:56.800
[Amit Varma]: when I was editing Pragati about the new world order and how, and you had kind of modified

00:18:56.800 --> 00:19:01.520
[Amit Varma]: the conventional way of thinking and added your own sort of lens to it. Tell me a little

00:19:01.520 --> 00:19:05.480
[Guest 2]: bit about that because I found it very insightful and fascinating. Yeah. So let's look at what

00:19:05.480 --> 00:19:11.400
[Guest 2]: this term world order means, right? So the world order, this, I'm taking this definition

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:17.000
[Guest 2]: from Kissinger's book by this name. So he describes the world order as a concept held

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:23.040
[Guest 2]: by a region or civilization about the nature of just arrangements and the distribution

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:28.120
[Guest 2]: of power thought to be applicable to the whole world. Okay. So this is the definition. So

00:19:28.120 --> 00:19:32.720
[Guest 2]: if this concept is applicable to the entire world, it is called an international order.

00:19:32.720 --> 00:19:36.400
[Guest 2]: If it applies only to a small region, it is called a regional order. Okay. So that is

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:42.400
[Guest 2]: what world order is. The two important words in this is just arrangements. And the second

00:19:42.400 --> 00:19:48.720
[Guest 2]: concept is power distribution of power. Okay. So this is what the central theme of any world

00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:54.160
[Guest 2]: order is. Okay. So basically just arrangement ties to this concept of legitimacy. Why is

00:19:54.160 --> 00:19:59.460
[Guest 2]: legitimacy important? Because if you have a set of commonly accepted rules that define

00:19:59.460 --> 00:20:04.880
[Guest 2]: the limits of permissible power for another state, then governing the world is easier,

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:11.240
[Guest 2]: right? So for example, when US propagated this idea of democracy, and now that was central

00:20:11.240 --> 00:20:15.280
[Guest 2]: to many of their actions in foreign policy, whether it actually led to democracy or not

00:20:15.280 --> 00:20:20.920
[Guest 2]: is a different thing, but it was in the name of democracy. So they build that concept and

00:20:20.920 --> 00:20:26.200
[Guest 2]: because they became the most powerful nation state, all of us think in terms of that same

00:20:26.200 --> 00:20:30.720
[Guest 2]: view, right? So now democracy, all actions of foreign policy are also seen from this

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:37.080
[Guest 2]: frame. So that becomes an important part. So that is about legitimacy. The second part

00:20:37.080 --> 00:20:42.880
[Guest 2]: is distribution of power. So you will not be able to do any of these things until and

00:20:42.880 --> 00:20:48.080
[Guest 2]: unless you have sufficient power to actually enforce things on other nations.

00:20:48.080 --> 00:20:54.120
[Amit Varma]: In fact, isn't the notion of just therefore also determined by power balances, like the

00:20:54.120 --> 00:20:59.080
[Amit Varma]: most powerful, especially if they are hegemonically powerful, like the USA will then define what

00:20:59.080 --> 00:21:01.120
[Amit Varma]: is just as you are saying in the case of democracy?

00:21:01.120 --> 00:21:06.080
[Guest 2]: Absolutely. Yeah, that's what I'm saying. That's why in my definition, great powers

00:21:06.080 --> 00:21:11.640
[Guest 2]: don't seek just power, they seek authority. And authority is a combination of power and

00:21:11.640 --> 00:21:16.640
[Guest 2]: legitimacy. Okay, so basically, once they achieve power, they make certain things which

00:21:16.640 --> 00:21:22.280
[Guest 2]: are in their own benefit common across the world. So democracy, free trade, for example,

00:21:22.280 --> 00:21:28.360
[Guest 2]: what US thought is important for them are now seen as the gold standard by a lot of

00:21:28.360 --> 00:21:33.560
[Guest 2]: countries, right? So those became the standards against which all countries started evaluating

00:21:33.560 --> 00:21:37.920
[Guest 2]: their own foreign policy. So that is the power of so power is important.

00:21:37.920 --> 00:21:42.440
[Guest 2]: Power is everything, basically. In foreign, if we see the realism school of

00:21:42.440 --> 00:21:45.240
[Guest 2]: international affairs, which I think more or less we agree to.

00:21:45.240 --> 00:21:48.440
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I think more or less we agree on that. I mean, Pranay has spoken about all three

00:21:48.440 --> 00:21:51.720
[Guest 1]: concepts and what you will see, at least in my work, what you will see is you will see

00:21:51.720 --> 00:21:55.560
[Guest 1]: all three of them being reflected that you know, there are ways in which you can leverage

00:21:55.560 --> 00:21:59.760
[Guest 1]: leaders, individuals, institutions within a country to shape narratives and therefore

00:21:59.760 --> 00:22:04.720
[Guest 1]: shape states policy, there is a utility, obviously, to international institutions, not just from

00:22:04.720 --> 00:22:08.320
[Guest 1]: a cooperative point of view, which is where sort of liberal internationalism comes into

00:22:08.320 --> 00:22:12.240
[Guest 1]: play. But that's also where power dynamics play out. I mean, the fact that today you

00:22:12.240 --> 00:22:17.840
[Guest 1]: have, you know, the Chinese wanting to have a specific have used UN resolutions reflect

00:22:17.840 --> 00:22:21.800
[Guest 1]: Xi Jinping thought or something like that, or shared community of common destiny is because

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:26.160
[Guest 1]: they see value in it. That is how you create authority. The fact that you want to end up

00:22:26.160 --> 00:22:32.400
[Guest 1]: having the definition of universal human rights be altered to reflect certain particularistic

00:22:32.400 --> 00:22:36.840
[Guest 1]: conditions of each nation so that you know, I can have my own set of human rights whereas

00:22:36.840 --> 00:22:41.480
[Guest 1]: you can have a different set is also where you want to shape sort of these norms, because

00:22:41.480 --> 00:22:45.000
[Guest 1]: these norms also eventually determine where authority lies. And you can see this currently

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:48.560
[Guest 1]: being played out between the US and the Chinese. So I think that all of this sort of has very

00:22:48.560 --> 00:22:53.040
[Guest 1]: real world implications, which is what I wanted to sort of get at is that when you apply some

00:22:53.040 --> 00:22:57.840
[Guest 1]: of these theories in the real world, you will not necessarily see neat distinctions, the

00:22:57.840 --> 00:23:01.080
[Guest 1]: real world is far more messy. So you'll see these things interplaying with each other,

00:23:01.080 --> 00:23:05.360
[Guest 1]: you'll see all of this happening, but power will remain sort of central to all of this.

00:23:05.360 --> 00:23:10.640
[Guest 1]: It is where power defined as also economic strength and that translates into military

00:23:10.640 --> 00:23:14.560
[Guest 1]: power and the rest of it that will essentially define where you stand in the sort of global

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:18.600
[Guest 1]: pecking order and how much you're able to influence. And the objective of the influence,

00:23:18.600 --> 00:23:23.080
[Guest 1]: like Rana said, is Yoko Shima. And that's from our point of view. But if I was to look

00:23:23.080 --> 00:23:26.360
[Guest 1]: at and I study China, so if you look at from a Chinese point of view, the objective is

00:23:26.360 --> 00:23:32.160
[Guest 1]: not necessarily Yoko Shima, the objective is broad objective is to ensure that the Communist

00:23:32.160 --> 00:23:37.200
[Guest 1]: Party remains in power and maintains its control over so called dominance of leadership of

00:23:37.200 --> 00:23:41.860
[Guest 1]: the Chinese people. However, you want to classify the Chinese people, not just who are in mainland,

00:23:41.860 --> 00:23:45.920
[Guest 1]: but who are probably even overseas Chinese, who are probably even people of Chinese descent

00:23:45.920 --> 00:23:50.480
[Guest 1]: living in places like Singapore, to have some sort of a legitimate authority to be speaking

00:23:50.480 --> 00:23:55.960
[Guest 1]: on their behalf and governing on their behalf. And I think Yoko Shima for them is an outcome

00:23:55.960 --> 00:24:00.920
[Guest 1]: that allows me to maintain my legitimacy, which is very different from how the means

00:24:00.920 --> 00:24:04.560
[Guest 1]: and it's a means. So if you look at that, that's very different from how we look at

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:08.600
[Guest 1]: from what India's sort of foreign policy objective should be what the primary goal of our foreign

00:24:08.600 --> 00:24:11.880
[Guest 1]: policy should be. So these can differ for different different countries in different

00:24:11.880 --> 00:24:16.080
[Guest 1]: different states. And I think that's where sort of I would draw the distinction between

00:24:16.080 --> 00:24:20.200
[Guest 1]: how we look at foreign policy for one state or another state and what sort of models can

00:24:20.200 --> 00:24:24.040
[Guest 1]: be drawn. So Yoko Shima need not necessarily be for everybody. But that's what we believe

00:24:24.040 --> 00:24:27.960
[Guest 2]: should be there for India. Actually, I mean, that's a perfect point for me to discuss a

00:24:27.960 --> 00:24:33.200
[Guest 2]: dilemma that we face while discussing both public policy and foreign policy. So as you

00:24:33.200 --> 00:24:38.600
[Guest 2]: know, when we are talking about the domestic sphere, we generally talk about liberalism,

00:24:38.600 --> 00:24:42.920
[Guest 2]: pluralism, freedom of all sorts, which are close to us. But when we talk about foreign

00:24:42.920 --> 00:24:49.080
[Guest 2]: policy, these principles don't necessarily apply. So in a sense, it is necessary for

00:24:49.080 --> 00:24:54.280
[Guest 2]: us to maintain a cognitive dissonance. When we are talking about domestic policy, we talk

00:24:54.280 --> 00:24:58.960
[Guest 2]: about freedom, pluralism, because that is the moral framework of our constitution and

00:24:58.960 --> 00:25:05.960
[Guest 2]: what we want India to also be more and more free, liberal, open, etc. But that's not how

00:25:05.960 --> 00:25:11.160
[Guest 2]: the international system operates. The international system is still Matsya Naya, what we discussed.

00:25:11.160 --> 00:25:16.400
[Guest 2]: And hence, when we talk about international relations, we have to discuss about power,

00:25:16.400 --> 00:25:23.400
[Guest 2]: about amorality. So this is a conflict which exists and you have to try to balance. And

00:25:23.400 --> 00:25:27.560
[Amit Varma]: just thinking about like one, you know, reason for that, obviously, would be that from now

00:25:27.560 --> 00:25:32.080
[Amit Varma]: from the workings of society, we know enough to know that all interactions are a positive

00:25:32.080 --> 00:25:36.880
[Amit Varma]: sum game, which is why freedom is good and coercion is bad. And that's how societies

00:25:36.880 --> 00:25:41.920
[Amit Varma]: progress. But foreign relations is often looked upon in most of the traditional frames as

00:25:41.920 --> 00:25:46.280
[Amit Varma]: a zero sum game where one country will win at the expense of another. And do you think

00:25:46.280 --> 00:25:51.760
[Amit Varma]: then that frame needs to be modified? Because honestly, all voluntary interactions between

00:25:51.760 --> 00:25:57.000
[Amit Varma]: individuals leave both people better off. That is also the same between countries. So

00:25:57.000 --> 00:26:01.360
[Amit Varma]: is there any way perhaps like, is it a vicious cycle of thinking in zero sum terms that if

00:26:01.360 --> 00:26:05.880
[Amit Varma]: everyone else does it, you have to also? And is there then a way of breaking that?

00:26:05.880 --> 00:26:10.520
[Guest 2]: Yeah, actually, people have tried to break it through, like we discussed about constructivism

00:26:10.520 --> 00:26:16.160
[Guest 2]: and other liberalism frames, they have been applied, but they haven't stood to empirical

00:26:16.160 --> 00:26:22.960
[Guest 2]: scrutiny, especially liberalism as a way forward in international relations, because you still

00:26:22.960 --> 00:26:28.200
[Guest 2]: see nation states, because there is no one government, nation states doing whatever it

00:26:28.200 --> 00:26:32.800
[Guest 2]: takes to increase their own power. And they might use that increased power for betterment

00:26:32.800 --> 00:26:38.560
[Guest 2]: of their own people, more liberalism, freedom inside their states. But when it comes to

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:44.320
[Guest 2]: interstate relations, the reality has been still that it is zero sum.

00:26:44.320 --> 00:26:49.200
[Amit Varma]: And as a complete aside, it also strikes me that I see a similar dissonance in everybody's

00:26:49.200 --> 00:26:53.400
[Amit Varma]: lives, not between, you know, what if the policies they favor within the country and

00:26:53.400 --> 00:26:57.520
[Amit Varma]: international relations, because most people aren't thinking about international relations,

00:26:57.520 --> 00:27:04.040
[Amit Varma]: but simply in terms of how they think of their personal ethics, and how they think of political

00:27:04.040 --> 00:27:09.480
[Amit Varma]: philosophy, like, for example, one passion project that I'm kind of working on, is sort

00:27:09.480 --> 00:27:15.160
[Amit Varma]: of explain how, like, there are two important questions to which people usually have separate

00:27:15.160 --> 00:27:20.200
[Amit Varma]: answers. And the first question is, what is a good way for me to live my life? What is

00:27:20.200 --> 00:27:25.000
[Amit Varma]: a virtuous way for me to live my life? And the second question is, how should the state

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:30.200
[Amit Varma]: interact with society? And most people have separate answers to both of them. For example,

00:27:30.200 --> 00:27:33.800
[Amit Varma]: in their personal lives, I often tell people, including leftist friends of mine that in

00:27:33.800 --> 00:27:38.160
[Amit Varma]: our personal lives, we're all libertarian, we respect the autonomy of others, we don't

00:27:38.160 --> 00:27:43.240
[Amit Varma]: coerce them, we respect their consent, you know, when you and I go out to a restaurant,

00:27:43.240 --> 00:27:47.880
[Amit Varma]: we won't force each other to eat what we want that person to eat, we won't force the other

00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:52.520
[Amit Varma]: person to pay for the meal, and so on and so forth. But it's different with the state.

00:27:52.520 --> 00:27:56.560
[Amit Varma]: And what I have come to through many years of churn and thinking and changing my mind

00:27:56.560 --> 00:28:01.080
[Amit Varma]: is that I view both through the same lens, which is the lens of consent and coercion,

00:28:01.080 --> 00:28:05.360
[Amit Varma]: that coercion is bad, and you have to respect consent. And that if there is something that

00:28:05.360 --> 00:28:10.040
[Amit Varma]: is wrong for one individual or one group of individuals to do to another, it is also wrong

00:28:10.040 --> 00:28:14.400
[Amit Varma]: for the state to do it to you. But this is a complete tangent. And I think we got on

00:28:14.400 --> 00:28:19.200
[Amit Varma]: the tangent because you were saying we instead of I, so I apologize for that. Let's come

00:28:19.200 --> 00:28:25.560
[Amit Varma]: to India then, in terms of the purpose of foreign policy, what do you think it should

00:28:25.560 --> 00:28:29.880
[Amit Varma]: be? And you guys have both articulated that you think it should be Yogakshema. But what

00:28:29.880 --> 00:28:35.200
[Amit Varma]: has it been historically in the past? What is it today? Like, is there sort of a consensus

00:28:35.200 --> 00:28:40.480
[Amit Varma]: on this within the foreign policy establishment? Has it been changing over time? Like, you

00:28:40.480 --> 00:28:45.760
[Amit Varma]: know, you might want to be self-aggrandizing as a nation and project power outside and

00:28:45.760 --> 00:28:49.800
[Amit Varma]: whatever, or you could be insular like China was for the longest time and be happy as long

00:28:49.800 --> 00:28:54.600
[Amit Varma]: as no one interferes with you. Or you could care about Yogakshema and say that, you know,

00:28:54.600 --> 00:28:59.840
[Amit Varma]: our end is the prosperity of our people, peaceful prosperity, and whatever gets us that is kosher.

00:28:59.840 --> 00:29:01.280
[Amit Varma]: So you know, how have those evolved?

00:29:01.280 --> 00:29:08.280
[Guest 2]: So I think on the practice side of things, it does, Yogakshema has been one of the views.

00:29:08.280 --> 00:29:13.240
[Guest 2]: So it's not articulated in that way, but prosperity of Indians and let's say that foreign policy

00:29:13.240 --> 00:29:19.920
[Guest 2]: should actually lead to economic growth, it should help us more Indians becoming prosperous.

00:29:19.920 --> 00:29:24.120
[Guest 2]: That is sort of been the theme of foreign policy right from independence. But there

00:29:24.120 --> 00:29:28.500
[Guest 2]: have been other elements to it as well. Like I said, territorial integrity has sometimes

00:29:28.500 --> 00:29:34.400
[Guest 2]: come in as an important point of view, or extending India's power to other places. Or

00:29:34.400 --> 00:29:40.280
[Guest 2]: some people are also articulated as maintaining India's predominant position in our neighborhood

00:29:40.280 --> 00:29:44.680
[Guest 2]: might be an important view. So there have been a mix of these ideas. But because we

00:29:44.680 --> 00:29:51.040
[Guest 2]: are a democracy, I think this idea of foreign policy should ultimately lead to welfare of

00:29:51.040 --> 00:29:56.000
[Guest 2]: Indians is somewhat remained common over the last 50-60 years.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:29:59.480
[Guest 1]: I think it has remained common, but like Pranay said, there are multiple other strands. And

00:29:59.480 --> 00:30:04.000
[Guest 1]: at least I mean, I won't necessarily go back to the 50-60s, I wasn't there. But my sense

00:30:04.000 --> 00:30:08.160
[Guest 1]: of things at that point in time was that there was a greater interest in influencing global

00:30:08.160 --> 00:30:11.520
[Guest 1]: events. Because that was seen, as you said, a sense of self-aggrandizement, a sense of

00:30:11.520 --> 00:30:12.760
[Amit Varma]: we have a greater role to play.

00:30:12.760 --> 00:30:13.760
[Amit Varma]: We matter.

00:30:13.760 --> 00:30:17.040
[Guest 1]: We matter. And that's how we matter. Because when we sort of do these things, because you're

00:30:17.040 --> 00:30:20.560
[Guest 1]: never going to matter with a country of, you know, hundreds of millions of really, really

00:30:20.560 --> 00:30:24.640
[Guest 1]: poor people, it's going to take you a long, long time. So that, I think, was one objective

00:30:24.640 --> 00:30:30.120
[Guest 1]: going back to history. I think another objective, and which I see more recently, is that foreign

00:30:30.120 --> 00:30:34.440
[Guest 1]: policy is a tool for domestic legitimacy in terms of just popular support. The idea that

00:30:34.440 --> 00:30:38.040
[Guest 1]: the Prime Minister over the last number of years now has gone abroad to say that, and

00:30:38.040 --> 00:30:41.240
[Guest 1]: his supporters have gone abroad to say things like, well, have you ever seen India being

00:30:41.240 --> 00:30:45.800
[Guest 1]: represented and spoken of so well? No, you've never seen that. And that's because of him

00:30:45.800 --> 00:30:51.120
[Guest 1]: or his machinery. I think there's a sense that that sense of international, the glory

00:30:51.120 --> 00:30:54.280
[Guest 1]: that you're getting internationally, the big crowds that are coming out there is going

00:30:54.280 --> 00:30:58.520
[Guest 1]: to reflect into domestic pride and therefore votes and therefore political legitimacy.

00:30:58.520 --> 00:31:02.080
[Guest 1]: I think that's also something that's being used now. That's not to say that it's not

00:31:02.080 --> 00:31:05.640
[Guest 1]: necessarily that you're not looking at development of India. I mean, when this government also

00:31:05.640 --> 00:31:08.840
[Guest 1]: came to power the first time, the objective was economic diplomacy is going to be one

00:31:08.840 --> 00:31:13.080
[Guest 1]: of the first things. And the objective of that is to, you know, push India's development

00:31:13.080 --> 00:31:16.840
[Guest 1]: forward. So I think there's a mix of objectives and a lot of it in the recent past, particularly

00:31:16.840 --> 00:31:21.800
[Guest 1]: in my recollection, the recent past, I don't recollect, say, even in the 80s, through the

00:31:21.800 --> 00:31:27.200
[Guest 1]: 90s, and even the early 2000s, Prime Minister's necessarily going abroad and using your clout

00:31:27.200 --> 00:31:31.600
[Guest 1]: abroad, or with overseas Indians as something to sell domestically saying this is how proud

00:31:31.600 --> 00:31:35.240
[Guest 1]: we've made you with this is how big India today is at the international stage. The argument

00:31:35.240 --> 00:31:38.320
[Guest 1]: may have been that we have growing economy and therefore we are now big and therefore

00:31:38.320 --> 00:31:42.320
[Guest 1]: we matter. But it was never the case of this individual makes you matter now. So therefore,

00:31:42.320 --> 00:31:46.240
[Amit Varma]: you should be voting for them. In fact, earlier when you were talking about how you know,

00:31:46.240 --> 00:31:50.480
[Amit Varma]: with China, it's not necessarily Yogakshema, it's a communist party over everything else.

00:31:50.480 --> 00:31:54.120
[Amit Varma]: And just thinking aloud, it seems to me a danger that that could even be happened in

00:31:54.120 --> 00:31:59.800
[Amit Varma]: India, where you know, if foreign validation is looked upon for, you know, as part of the

00:31:59.800 --> 00:32:04.640
[Amit Varma]: optics that raise your brand within India itself, then that's something dangerous, it

00:32:04.640 --> 00:32:09.840
[Amit Varma]: not need to be just it not need necessarily be at odds with, you know, what India's interest

00:32:09.840 --> 00:32:13.880
[Amit Varma]: is. So there is, you know, one theory as to why Mr. Modi travels abroad so much, which

00:32:13.880 --> 00:32:21.520
[Guest 2]: is to escape from the pollution of Delhi. For example, actually, the centrality of Pakistan

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:27.600
[Guest 2]: in India's foreign policy is a manifestation of that, right? Because ideally, in our view,

00:32:27.600 --> 00:32:33.360
[Guest 2]: again, foreign policy should be about we should try to ignore Pakistan as much as possible,

00:32:33.360 --> 00:32:38.160
[Guest 2]: right? Because you're not on the same level. Yeah, you're talking to a least common denominator,

00:32:38.160 --> 00:32:42.600
[Guest 2]: then you're always going to compare yourself with Pakistan. Why would you do that? Right?

00:32:42.600 --> 00:32:49.360
[Guest 2]: I mean, that would be defeating India's what India's wants itself to be. So as in the recent

00:32:49.360 --> 00:32:54.560
[Guest 2]: years, what you're seeing is Pakistan, again, becoming a central part of India's foreign

00:32:54.560 --> 00:32:59.760
[Guest 2]: policy, which it was moving away like us, for example, earlier, you if you would remember,

00:32:59.760 --> 00:33:04.640
[Guest 2]: you whenever the US President came to Delhi, he also made a trip to Islamabad, like that

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:10.680
[Guest 2]: was just the normal operation. But over the last 10 years, even in the US, this had changed,

00:33:10.680 --> 00:33:17.000
[Guest 2]: right? India and Pakistan were at different levels for the US. But now you see, again,

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:22.560
[Guest 2]: this idea being that we have to do things because Pakistan look at what they are doing,

00:33:22.560 --> 00:33:26.000
[Guest 2]: because they are doing that, why can't we do it, you know, so we are comparing ourselves

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:30.560
[Guest 2]: with Pakistan. And that is not necessarily leading to Yogakshem of Indians, it might

00:33:30.560 --> 00:33:35.680
[Guest 2]: lead to better prospects for a particular political party, but it might not be good

00:33:35.680 --> 00:33:39.680
[Guest 1]: for all Indians. Yeah, the only sort of corollary that I can think of in this context in the

00:33:39.680 --> 00:33:43.560
[Guest 1]: recent past is, so if you go back to about 10-12 years ago, there was this framework

00:33:43.560 --> 00:33:49.440
[Guest 1]: of Chindia, where China and India rising together, we'll make Bombay into Shanghai. That's sort

00:33:49.440 --> 00:33:53.240
[Guest 1]: of a comparison where you are trying to compare yourself. And to me, that was healthy comparison

00:33:53.240 --> 00:33:58.920
[Guest 1]: in some ways, because you were trying to look at emulating development, at least it's aspirational.

00:33:58.920 --> 00:34:02.600
[Guest 1]: But yeah, I mean, the idea that oh, this is where we are going. And you know, look, globally,

00:34:02.600 --> 00:34:07.080
[Guest 1]: we're being talked about in comparison with China, and whether it's a peer now, that could

00:34:07.080 --> 00:34:09.960
[Guest 1]: have been one way where you could sort of leverage foreign policy for domestic gain,

00:34:09.960 --> 00:34:13.480
[Guest 1]: saying that, look, now we're in the conversation at this table. Today, that's shifted completely,

00:34:13.480 --> 00:34:17.080
[Guest 1]: we're in a completely different table in terms of the conversation. But the idea that you

00:34:17.080 --> 00:34:20.540
[Guest 1]: know, this comparison with Pakistan, so you spoke about the US presence previously coming

00:34:20.540 --> 00:34:24.840
[Guest 1]: in this happening last year, when the Chinese foreign minister was supposed to come in September,

00:34:24.840 --> 00:34:29.320
[Guest 1]: apparently, we refused him basically saying you're coming via Pakistan, and we're unhappy

00:34:29.320 --> 00:34:34.040
[Guest 1]: with that. So come again, another time and don't come via Pakistan. Wow, that's a very

00:34:34.040 --> 00:34:41.400
[Guest 1]: silly tantrum. Yeah. And he came in December. So, and not via Pakistan. So yeah, so I think

00:34:41.400 --> 00:34:45.440
[Guest 1]: it's still a raw nerve internationally in that sense. But domestically, it probably

00:34:45.440 --> 00:34:49.120
[Guest 1]: pays political dividends quite significantly. So you keep continuing to use that. So that's

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:52.520
[Amit Varma]: a trade off. And if you care much more about your domestic whatever than the Jogokshama

00:34:52.520 --> 00:34:53.520
[Guest 2]: of your people.

00:34:53.520 --> 00:34:57.960
[Guest 2]: So just one point related to that important point of peaceful enjoyment of prosperity

00:34:57.960 --> 00:35:04.960
[Guest 2]: is economic growth, right? The growth is important. So for a long time, like Nitin and all of

00:35:04.960 --> 00:35:10.120
[Guest 2]: us also talk about what is India's foreign policy towards us, it is 8% economic growth.

00:35:10.120 --> 00:35:14.920
[Guest 2]: What is India's foreign policy towards Pakistan, it is 8% economic growth. Similarly, for against

00:35:14.920 --> 00:35:20.400
[Guest 2]: many countries, it is about economic growth, right? As long as we are able to do that,

00:35:20.400 --> 00:35:25.320
[Guest 2]: and we use foreign policy to further enhance our growth, we are on the right track. Otherwise,

00:35:25.320 --> 00:35:28.920
[Amit Varma]: we are going in the wrong direction. And I want to elaborate on the moral importance

00:35:28.920 --> 00:35:34.520
[Amit Varma]: of economic growth. Like if, for example, you agree that a democracy, your dharma is

00:35:34.520 --> 00:35:39.960
[Amit Varma]: to uplift your people. Fact to remember is that every 1% rise in GDP gets 2 million people

00:35:39.960 --> 00:35:43.880
[Amit Varma]: out of poverty, a figure which I first learned from your colleague Nitin Pai, in fact. And

00:35:43.880 --> 00:35:47.400
[Amit Varma]: therefore, there is a moral imperative to growth. Therefore, when your growth slips

00:35:47.400 --> 00:35:52.920
[Amit Varma]: from 7% to 4%, the opportunity cost of that is 6 million people who are still in poverty

00:35:52.920 --> 00:35:57.280
[Amit Varma]: who would not have been. How is that not something to get your blood boiling? How is that any

00:35:57.280 --> 00:36:01.560
[Amit Varma]: less than, you know, the other humanitarian crimes carried out by this regime or that?

00:36:01.560 --> 00:36:06.640
[Guest 2]: Totally agree. So that's why when we talk about foreign policy, it is with this frame,

00:36:06.640 --> 00:36:12.960
[Guest 2]: right? Let's talk about growth and how we can use foreign policy to increase our prospects

00:36:12.960 --> 00:36:18.080
[Amit Varma]: and bring prosperity for all Indians. So I have a question about India, which is that

00:36:18.080 --> 00:36:23.280
[Amit Varma]: however, foreign policy may sometimes be used as a tool of optics by the party in power.

00:36:23.280 --> 00:36:28.120
[Amit Varma]: Is it basically fundamentally run by a deep state kind of apparatus in the sense that

00:36:28.120 --> 00:36:33.080
[Amit Varma]: is it just the dip, your external affairs ministry or whatever, where they have their

00:36:33.080 --> 00:36:37.440
[Amit Varma]: carders and they have everything and they run it and therefore policy will be more or

00:36:37.440 --> 00:36:43.640
[Amit Varma]: less consistent and stable through different political regimes. And, you know, politicians

00:36:43.640 --> 00:36:47.440
[Amit Varma]: may use foreign policy for a little window dressing here and there, but it's really the

00:36:47.440 --> 00:36:52.680
[Amit Varma]: deep state which is handling things. For example, exemplified perhaps by the appointment of

00:36:52.680 --> 00:36:58.480
[Amit Varma]: Mr. Jaishankar who's, you know, a career foreign affairs bureaucrat who is now in charge of

00:36:58.480 --> 00:37:02.960
[Amit Varma]: the external affairs ministry at the time of recording this on Jan 24. It's a strange

00:37:02.960 --> 00:37:07.120
[Amit Varma]: world one never knows. So is that the case or do politicians have a greater impact? No,

00:37:07.120 --> 00:37:12.880
[Guest 2]: I would say I'll give a few examples to illustrate, right? Just look at what Manmohan Singh's

00:37:12.880 --> 00:37:18.800
[Guest 2]: government did with the U.S. on the nuclear deal, right? They staked their government's

00:37:18.800 --> 00:37:24.960
[Guest 2]: position for that particular foreign policy action and it did have rewards, right? That

00:37:24.960 --> 00:37:31.760
[Guest 2]: single decision led to India and U.S. relations being taken to a different level. So political

00:37:31.760 --> 00:37:36.440
[Guest 2]: will, political decision making matters a lot, just like in any other foreign policy.

00:37:36.440 --> 00:37:42.440
[Guest 2]: So basic tenets might remain the same, just like in economic policy, broadly everyone

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:47.000
[Guest 2]: in the government also realizes that economic growth is important. But how would you want

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:51.880
[Guest 2]: to reach that economic growth differs, right? This government is increasing import duties

00:37:51.880 --> 00:37:56.080
[Guest 2]: in the hope of saying that growth will be important. Which is bizarrely ignorant. So

00:37:56.080 --> 00:38:01.720
[Guest 2]: the actual practice might in fact be very different. So even in foreign policy, that's

00:38:01.720 --> 00:38:08.160
[Guest 2]: the case. So even though people recognize that the ultimate goal is more prosperity

00:38:08.160 --> 00:38:14.160
[Guest 2]: for Indians, but the practice is different and that depends on the political will, what

00:38:14.160 --> 00:38:18.120
[Guest 1]: the government of that day and age thinks. So I mean, I think if you go back to history

00:38:18.120 --> 00:38:23.200
[Guest 1]: and if you look at it, when India became independent, the political class obviously had the dominant

00:38:23.200 --> 00:38:27.400
[Guest 1]: role in foreign policy making. I mean, Nehru ran India's foreign policy. Over time, obviously,

00:38:27.400 --> 00:38:30.880
[Guest 1]: the bureaucracy develops and the bureaucracy gets institutionalized in certain values,

00:38:30.880 --> 00:38:35.320
[Guest 1]: in certain sense of what our interests are and what our approaches are. Subsequently

00:38:35.320 --> 00:38:39.200
[Guest 1]: making sort of pivoting is very difficult because that's where I think sort of deep

00:38:39.200 --> 00:38:43.640
[Guest 1]: state in the sense sort of fixes in. And if you look at, if you listen to former bureaucrats,

00:38:43.640 --> 00:38:48.160
[Guest 1]: former IFS folks, former ambassadors, you get that sense that there is a certain viewpoint

00:38:48.160 --> 00:38:52.800
[Guest 1]: that they come from and to take some of those leaps and one of the leaps was what Pranay

00:38:52.800 --> 00:38:56.720
[Guest 1]: mentioned, which was the nuclear deal. It was a very, very difficult process to go through

00:38:56.720 --> 00:39:02.120
[Guest 1]: that and there's a lot of not just political, but also bureaucratic sort of pushback against

00:39:02.120 --> 00:39:06.000
[Guest 1]: something like that. But that's made and that's again where the political class sort of intervenes.

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:10.080
[Guest 1]: I think today what you see is that there is an institutionalized sense and I think this

00:39:10.080 --> 00:39:15.560
[Guest 1]: has to go back to the nuclear deal in that period of time over 10-12 years now. The sense

00:39:15.560 --> 00:39:19.560
[Guest 1]: that, actually not even 10-12 years ago, I think this goes back to the late 90s after

00:39:19.560 --> 00:39:23.240
[Guest 1]: we conducted the nuclear tests and the subsequent dialogue. Again, this is a political level

00:39:23.240 --> 00:39:27.200
[Guest 1]: dialogue happening between Stuart Talbot and Juswan Singh and that shapes narratives.

00:39:27.200 --> 00:39:31.360
[Guest 1]: And then it takes us still about 10 years after that to do this nuclear deal, finalize

00:39:31.360 --> 00:39:32.360
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:39:32.360 --> 00:39:34.800
[Amit Varma]: But the dialogue happened through regimes, which is interesting.

00:39:34.800 --> 00:39:37.640
[Guest 1]: The dialogue began with Juswan Singh and Stuart Talbot and that was the dialogue with sort

00:39:37.640 --> 00:39:41.640
[Guest 1]: of normalized things, which is when Bill Clinton visited India in 2000. After that, and that

00:39:41.640 --> 00:39:44.920
[Guest 1]: was a big deal, right? Sanctions were placed against India and then Bill Clinton comes

00:39:44.920 --> 00:39:50.040
[Guest 1]: to India eventually. Subsequently, it takes about five years where we end up announcing

00:39:50.040 --> 00:39:53.440
[Guest 1]: this possibility of a nuclear deal. And even this possibility of the nuclear deal in the

00:39:53.440 --> 00:39:57.760
[Guest 1]: US, there is a pushback because this is George Bush wanting to do it and us taking on the

00:39:57.760 --> 00:40:01.200
[Guest 1]: opportunity with that. But there is a pushback in the US also, which led to therefore that

00:40:01.200 --> 00:40:05.280
[Guest 1]: 1-2-3 agreement going through such a long discussion. Even in India, there is resistance

00:40:05.280 --> 00:40:09.560
[Guest 1]: and that's why it takes you eventually so long. When you reach the agreement, subsequently,

00:40:09.560 --> 00:40:13.800
[Guest 1]: if you see whatever subsequent governments have sort of felt, whatever sort of the environments

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:16.880
[Guest 1]: have been, there have been certain sort of constants in how we've approached it. We've

00:40:16.880 --> 00:40:22.000
[Guest 1]: moved closer to the US, we've tried to balance the Chinese and we've tried to also figure

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:27.560
[Guest 1]: out a way where we can maintain economic growth in whatever way we can. And that's been sort

00:40:27.560 --> 00:40:30.520
[Guest 1]: of broadly our priorities without trying to get too controversial. We've tried to sort

00:40:30.520 --> 00:40:33.960
[Guest 1]: of keep somewhere equidistant where we don't get caught up in controversies, managing our

00:40:33.960 --> 00:40:37.280
[Guest 1]: relationship with Iran and the US pressure on Iran and all those things. To me, part

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:42.120
[Guest 1]: of that is political. But part of that is also how the bureaucracy sort of seeks stability

00:40:42.120 --> 00:40:46.640
[Guest 1]: because certain values get entrenched, certain opportunities, certain senses get entrenched.

00:40:46.640 --> 00:40:50.560
[Guest 1]: And then it's very difficult. You need something where the political establishment sort of

00:40:50.560 --> 00:40:55.360
[Guest 1]: pushes hard, bangs on heads and then you sort of push through something which can be transformative.

00:40:55.360 --> 00:41:00.420
[Guest 1]: So if today you were to ask somebody who feels that India must pivot, the world is changing

00:41:00.420 --> 00:41:05.600
[Guest 1]: drastically, India must pivot towards some sort of an alliance with the US, you will

00:41:05.600 --> 00:41:09.680
[Guest 1]: find a lot of inertia within the bureaucracy. You will find a lot of former ambassadors

00:41:09.680 --> 00:41:13.920
[Guest 1]: and bureaucrats saying, no, no, no, that's going too far. We can talk, we can do this

00:41:13.920 --> 00:41:18.160
[Guest 1]: and we can sort of find some sort of a modus vivendi, but we don't necessarily want to

00:41:18.160 --> 00:41:21.920
[Guest 1]: go down that road. And that's because you're institutionalising certain thought processes

00:41:21.920 --> 00:41:25.400
[Guest 1]: about risk taking, about where our interests lie and how our interests are sort of being

00:41:25.400 --> 00:41:29.040
[Guest 1]: shaped by the events. But you won't necessarily anticipate it because you're institutionalising

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:33.120
[Guest 1]: those things. So I think there is a deep state which gets entrenched over a period of time.

00:41:33.120 --> 00:41:36.400
[Guest 1]: There are points of time in India's history where politicians have sort of dominated this

00:41:36.400 --> 00:41:41.480
[Guest 1]: particular foreign policy framework. Yet I think for in much of post Nehruvian era, it's

00:41:41.480 --> 00:41:45.840
[Guest 1]: been the bureaucracy which has driven things. There have been moments where the politicians

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:49.200
[Guest 1]: have sort of taken charge, but much of the time it's I think it's a bureaucracy that's

00:41:49.200 --> 00:41:51.200
[Guest 1]: maintained things the way they are.

00:41:51.200 --> 00:41:56.640
[Amit Varma]: So would it be fair to say that there is therefore a status quo bias at play that among bureaucrats

00:41:56.640 --> 00:42:00.640
[Amit Varma]: that the safest thing is to do nothing because nothing can go wrong and you can't be blamed

00:42:00.640 --> 00:42:05.240
[Amit Varma]: for doing, you know, the usual whatever it is that you do. And therefore, if any drastic

00:42:05.240 --> 00:42:09.440
[Amit Varma]: actions or big changes from the past have to be done, they have to necessarily come

00:42:09.440 --> 00:42:10.440
[Amit Varma]: from politicians.

00:42:10.440 --> 00:42:14.680
[Guest 2]: Yes, I would agree with that. So there is a very famous quote in international which

00:42:14.680 --> 00:42:19.920
[Guest 2]: gets misused a lot is about there are no permanent friends or enemies, only permanent interests.

00:42:19.920 --> 00:42:25.320
[Guest 2]: Now let me corrupt it further and say that interests are semi-permanent. Okay, the interests

00:42:25.320 --> 00:42:30.640
[Guest 2]: also change but they are semi-permanent. So that's why you will see the status quo bias

00:42:30.640 --> 00:42:36.160
[Guest 2]: in the sense that largely interests of India across these have also remained the same and

00:42:36.160 --> 00:42:41.080
[Guest 2]: they have changed not with every government, but they have changed over say 20-30 years

00:42:41.080 --> 00:42:45.640
[Guest 2]: because you know, your interests will change if, when will they change? When your entire

00:42:45.640 --> 00:42:50.440
[Guest 2]: power in the international order also changes, right? Let's say if you have acquired more

00:42:50.440 --> 00:42:55.800
[Guest 2]: economic power or more military power, you have that many more instruments to achieve

00:42:55.800 --> 00:43:01.280
[Guest 2]: something, right? Let's say you want to ensure that Indians who are working in the Gulf are

00:43:01.280 --> 00:43:06.400
[Guest 2]: protected. But if you don't have a Navy to back that up, there's not much you can do.

00:43:06.400 --> 00:43:10.160
[Guest 2]: You will do status quo. You will just say, okay, have good relations with all countries

00:43:10.160 --> 00:43:15.320
[Guest 2]: in West Asia, balance all of them. Yeah, but that's pretty much it, right? But now imagine

00:43:15.320 --> 00:43:20.040
[Guest 2]: India is a much more powerful country in terms of the economic wherewithal and also in terms

00:43:20.040 --> 00:43:25.680
[Guest 2]: of military strength, then we can deploy things there. We can also have relationships with

00:43:25.680 --> 00:43:31.320
[Guest 2]: other countries, which will ensure that in times of emergency, Indians are repatriated

00:43:31.320 --> 00:43:37.860
[Guest 2]: in a much better way, right? So the dependence is on our own power. And if we have more power,

00:43:37.860 --> 00:43:42.960
[Guest 2]: it might not necessarily be status quo. We can do many more things. We can deliver pain

00:43:42.960 --> 00:43:48.200
[Guest 2]: to countries which act against us. And we can also provide benefits to countries which

00:43:48.200 --> 00:43:50.360
[Guest 2]: act according to us.

00:43:50.360 --> 00:43:54.720
[Amit Varma]: And what also strikes me here is that using the realist frame and putting power at the

00:43:54.720 --> 00:43:59.360
[Amit Varma]: center of everything means that India is playing multiple games at the same time. Like on one

00:43:59.360 --> 00:44:04.040
[Amit Varma]: hand, you have the US as this large power, and India has a history of not being particularly

00:44:04.040 --> 00:44:08.120
[Amit Varma]: close to them during the Cold War and so on. So, you know, there is this constant game

00:44:08.120 --> 00:44:12.000
[Amit Varma]: you're playing where you're trying to sort of maintain national pride, but also get closer

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:15.560
[Amit Varma]: to them and make them friendlier towards you. And at the same time, within the region, you

00:44:15.560 --> 00:44:21.000
[Amit Varma]: are the big boy in South Asia, and you want to sort of use that to consolidate your influence.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:24.600
[Amit Varma]: And at the same time, you're very aware that China is doing things in your neighborhood

00:44:24.600 --> 00:44:29.080
[Amit Varma]: in the Indian Ocean. And you also have therefore the imperative of at least balancing that

00:44:29.080 --> 00:44:33.420
[Amit Varma]: and looking after your interests. How is Indian thinking on all of these and we can go one

00:44:33.420 --> 00:44:38.640
[Amit Varma]: by one and not necessarily try to do a broad sweep one by one. If we talk about our attitude

00:44:38.640 --> 00:44:43.240
[Amit Varma]: towards the USA, towards China, towards the region, how has that sort of evolved over

00:44:43.240 --> 00:44:44.240
[Amit Varma]: the last 20-30 years?

00:44:44.240 --> 00:44:50.680
[Guest 2]: So, let's look at US first, probably. So, on the US, there was this article that an

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:56.280
[Guest 2]: interview that K Subramaniam gave for Pragati itself long back, where he articulated that

00:44:56.280 --> 00:45:01.920
[Guest 2]: if the world is going to be such that US is the number one and China is number two in

00:45:01.920 --> 00:45:08.160
[Guest 2]: the world, it is in India's interest to ensure that US is number one. So, that was sort of

00:45:08.160 --> 00:45:14.560
[Guest 2]: his articulation. But so, broadly, Indian foreign policy has taken that trend that US

00:45:14.560 --> 00:45:20.480
[Guest 2]: is important, even though there is very strong anti-Americanism in our, because of our previous

00:45:20.480 --> 00:45:25.320
[Guest 2]: history, Cold War, closeness with Russia and all that. But look at India, right? Our median

00:45:25.320 --> 00:45:33.000
[Guest 2]: age is 27. Most of the people are born after liberalization. So, and we all have had, you

00:45:33.000 --> 00:45:38.760
[Guest 2]: know, even at a cultural level, US has been close, right? Many people in Bangalore have

00:45:38.760 --> 00:45:45.320
[Guest 2]: worked for US companies, including me. So, there is that anti-Americanism, I think is

00:45:45.320 --> 00:45:50.880
[Guest 2]: slowly fading away. And that is a recognition from the US side as well, because the US game,

00:45:50.880 --> 00:45:56.920
[Guest 2]: big game is US is worried about China. And it realizes that to counter China, it needs

00:45:56.920 --> 00:46:02.120
[Guest 2]: a player, a middle power, which is of significant strength, which at the current stage only

00:46:02.120 --> 00:46:08.480
[Guest 2]: is India. So, now you see a convergence of both US wanting, seeing India at a different

00:46:08.480 --> 00:46:14.360
[Guest 2]: level than other players like Pakistan. And India also moving away from that anti-American

00:46:14.360 --> 00:46:20.560
[Guest 2]: attitude, which existed 20-30 years ago. So, over the last 10 years, there has been more

00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:25.960
[Guest 2]: convergence and US-India relationships have been much better than they were 20-30 years

00:46:25.960 --> 00:46:28.640
[Amit Varma]: ago. And is there a sort of balancing to be done

00:46:28.640 --> 00:46:33.120
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that we also want good relations with China? But is there a sort of balancing

00:46:33.120 --> 00:46:37.800
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that if they see us get too close with the US, they might get pissed off?

00:46:37.800 --> 00:46:42.400
[Guest 1]: Yeah, I mean, so there was a news report last week, which spoke about a Trump staffer, I

00:46:42.400 --> 00:46:46.320
[Guest 1]: think it was Scaramucci, but I can't remember which Trump staffer, but a former Trump staffer

00:46:46.320 --> 00:46:50.160
[Guest 1]: essentially saying that when Modi met Trump, Trump asked him, Trump, they were talking

00:46:50.160 --> 00:46:53.560
[Guest 1]: about China and Trump sort of made a remark saying, it's not like China is next to you,

00:46:53.560 --> 00:46:58.120
[Guest 1]: right? It's not like it's on the border with you. So, it is on the border with us, of course.

00:46:58.120 --> 00:47:03.040
[Guest 1]: And so, it's not just the fact that China is a large neighbour, which is next to us,

00:47:03.040 --> 00:47:09.120
[Guest 1]: which enjoys a massive asymmetry with us. China's per capita GDP today is over $10,000,

00:47:09.120 --> 00:47:15.040
[Guest 1]: five times more than ours. Its capacity to use its economic resources to create military

00:47:15.040 --> 00:47:19.760
[Guest 1]: power is far, far superior than ours. So, it enjoys a massive asymmetry from us. Secondly,

00:47:19.760 --> 00:47:25.360
[Guest 1]: we've got this long pending border dispute, which continues to be an irritant. Thirdly,

00:47:25.360 --> 00:47:29.520
[Guest 1]: China is one of our biggest trading partners. Our trade with the Chinese is today at $92,

00:47:29.520 --> 00:47:34.000
[Guest 1]: $93 billion a year. There's increasing Chinese investment coming in India. So, that's an

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:37.840
[Guest 1]: opportunity. In the last three, four years, there's been about $9, $10 billion worth of

00:47:37.840 --> 00:47:42.000
[Guest 1]: Chinese investment coming in, largely in India's tech sector. But apart from that, also in

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:45.320
[Guest 1]: construction and other things. So, there's an opportunity that it presents, but there's

00:47:45.320 --> 00:47:49.680
[Guest 1]: also a threat that the Chinese present, which is the fact that they are not just an asymmetrically

00:47:49.680 --> 00:47:54.000
[Guest 1]: large neighbour sitting next door to us with a border dispute from us. They also have a

00:47:54.000 --> 00:47:59.240
[Guest 1]: very close relationship with Pakistan, which is a fundamental irritant for India in its

00:47:59.240 --> 00:48:02.560
[Guest 1]: trajectory to grow further. And there's long standing hostility with the Chinese have sort

00:48:02.560 --> 00:48:07.720
[Guest 1]: of furthered by helping develop Pakistan's weapons, nuclear industry. And it's furthering

00:48:07.720 --> 00:48:12.680
[Guest 1]: that also right now, because it's also investing in Pakistan's Navy right now. And as that

00:48:12.680 --> 00:48:16.480
[Guest 1]: sort of develops, it creates more problems over India. Because, I mean, everybody remembers

00:48:16.480 --> 00:48:20.680
[Guest 1]: the Masood Azhar saga, where the Chinese constantly supported Masood Azhar's, the not listing

00:48:20.680 --> 00:48:24.520
[Guest 1]: of Masood Azhar as a UN designated terrorist. So, there are these fundamental contradictions

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:28.200
[Guest 1]: that we have with China. There's an opportunity there and there's a threat there. And my sense

00:48:28.200 --> 00:48:31.680
[Guest 1]: is that what we should be doing and what we are trying to do, although we're not necessarily

00:48:31.680 --> 00:48:36.020
[Guest 1]: doing as well as we could have, is to try and not just balance it in terms of our relationship

00:48:36.020 --> 00:48:40.360
[Guest 1]: with America, and also trying to invest in our domestic capacities, because that's fundamentally

00:48:40.360 --> 00:48:44.000
[Guest 1]: what is going to be needed to deter the Chinese. So, this is a four step thing that we need

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:47.940
[Guest 1]: to do. We need to engage with them. We don't necessarily engage with them well. Our engagements

00:48:47.940 --> 00:48:52.640
[Guest 1]: have been, at leader levels, yes, we do engage. You know, before even Modi was meeting Xi

00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:56.760
[Guest 1]: Jinping for informal summits and sipping coconuts, you know, there were meetings between Indian

00:48:56.760 --> 00:49:00.200
[Guest 1]: leaders and Chinese leaders. I mean, Manmohan Singh and Hu Jintao met a number of times

00:49:00.200 --> 00:49:03.680
[Guest 1]: and that's when sort of the big bonhomie was happening. So, that's one thing. But also

00:49:03.680 --> 00:49:08.680
[Guest 1]: at sort of society levels, governmental levels, institutional levels within governments, at

00:49:08.680 --> 00:49:12.320
[Guest 1]: different levels, we need to be engaging with them because we don't necessarily understand

00:49:12.320 --> 00:49:17.160
[Guest 1]: how that system operates. And a classy example is the engagements at our armed forces. The

00:49:17.160 --> 00:49:22.000
[Guest 1]: fact that India and China have been talking about setting up a hotline, a crisis de-escalation

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:26.200
[Guest 1]: hotline between the armed forces for years now, at least publicly this government said

00:49:26.200 --> 00:49:31.000
[Guest 1]: so two years ago. And it just announced this month that we are in a position where a hotline

00:49:31.000 --> 00:49:34.560
[Guest 1]: will be set up. And the reason that you couldn't set this hotline up is because India said,

00:49:34.560 --> 00:49:37.960
[Guest 1]: we have the Director General of Military Operations, that person will be in charge. Who is your

00:49:37.960 --> 00:49:42.880
[Guest 1]: equivalent at that side? And neither could we, neither could they identify the equivalent.

00:49:42.880 --> 00:49:47.640
[Guest 1]: So just this sort of sense of lack of understanding of each other's systems and sort of being

00:49:47.640 --> 00:49:51.040
[Guest 1]: able to harmonise that. So, we need to engage with them. We also need to balance them, which

00:49:51.040 --> 00:49:54.360
[Guest 1]: is what we are doing with the US, which is what we're doing when we partner with Japan,

00:49:54.360 --> 00:49:57.840
[Guest 1]: with Australia, this idea that we are building up this quadrilateral group, which is not

00:49:57.840 --> 00:50:02.280
[Guest 1]: an alliance, but some sort of a loose coming together of like-minded countries. Most important

00:50:02.280 --> 00:50:05.760
[Guest 1]: to this is not the fact that we have these countries working with us, but the fact that

00:50:05.760 --> 00:50:09.960
[Guest 1]: we work with them to develop our own capacity, our own military capacity. And we're sort

00:50:09.960 --> 00:50:14.400
[Guest 1]: of gradually taking steps to do that. In terms of deterrence, the capacity building will

00:50:14.400 --> 00:50:17.800
[Guest 1]: work. Nuclear weapons are an important part of the deterrence, but also the fact that

00:50:17.800 --> 00:50:21.720
[Guest 1]: we need to be able to bolster our border defences, we need to be able to build infrastructure,

00:50:21.720 --> 00:50:26.240
[Guest 1]: we need to be able to spend on our Navy. And for all of this, our economy is fundamental.

00:50:26.240 --> 00:50:31.980
[Guest 1]: And the last bit over there, in terms of this framework of engagement, balancing, deterrence

00:50:31.980 --> 00:50:36.080
[Guest 1]: is collaboration. And that's where I sort of tie in the economy. The Chinese today are

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:39.960
[Guest 1]: massively capital rich, they want to spend money, they want better returns. India can

00:50:39.960 --> 00:50:43.560
[Guest 1]: potentially offer a market where they can get better returns. We've not been able to

00:50:43.560 --> 00:50:47.160
[Guest 1]: attract the kind of investment, although there's 8 and 9 billion that I've said about, but

00:50:47.160 --> 00:50:50.200
[Guest 1]: there's much more investment from the Chinese that could come into dummy infrastructure,

00:50:50.200 --> 00:50:53.600
[Guest 1]: which hasn't come in. They're doing this around the world, but they're not doing this in India.

00:50:53.600 --> 00:50:57.440
[Guest 1]: We should be trying to attract that money in, and that requires regulatory clarity in

00:50:57.440 --> 00:51:00.600
[Guest 1]: India. So that's where we need to collaborate with them, not just on infrastructure, but

00:51:00.600 --> 00:51:04.880
[Guest 1]: also maybe on say digital technologies, talking to them about cyber governance and these sorts

00:51:04.880 --> 00:51:08.360
[Guest 1]: of things, talking to them about data protection, which are all going to be norms which are

00:51:08.360 --> 00:51:11.520
[Guest 1]: going to be shaped internationally. And we need to work with them on these things to

00:51:11.520 --> 00:51:15.960
[Guest 1]: be able to collaborate where we can, leverage what we can to be able to then build our capacity

00:51:15.960 --> 00:51:19.560
[Guest 1]: and deter them. So yes, while we build our relationship with the US, this is a neighbor

00:51:19.560 --> 00:51:22.720
[Guest 1]: on our border, which we need to manage well. And this is a framework through which we can

00:51:22.720 --> 00:51:23.720
[Guest 2]: manage them.

00:51:23.720 --> 00:51:29.280
[Guest 2]: I just want to tie that into the US-India question. So broadly, the way I see it as

00:51:29.280 --> 00:51:35.200
[Guest 2]: India's US relationship, there are three schools of thought. One is purely a retaliatory school

00:51:35.200 --> 00:51:39.040
[Guest 2]: of thought, which says, why should India do anything to the US because US keeps supporting

00:51:39.040 --> 00:51:45.520
[Guest 2]: Pakistan still. It still supports the Pakistani military. It gives F-16s to them and all that.

00:51:45.520 --> 00:51:49.720
[Guest 2]: So that's a retaliatory school in nature. It is very low on realism because it is not

00:51:49.720 --> 00:51:54.720
[Guest 2]: taking into account what US can do to India, the benefits it can give. That is one school

00:51:54.720 --> 00:51:58.560
[Guest 2]: of thought. The second school of thought is purely bandwagoning, which I told you about

00:51:58.560 --> 00:52:04.120
[Guest 2]: that we should try to ensure that India, if US is the number one and China is number two,

00:52:04.120 --> 00:52:08.160
[Guest 2]: US should be number one. We should try to prolong that. The third school of thought

00:52:08.160 --> 00:52:12.320
[Guest 2]: is what Manoj was talking about and what we sort of believe in about India trying to be

00:52:12.320 --> 00:52:17.680
[Guest 2]: a swing power. Basically, India's capability should be that it should be able to deliver

00:52:17.680 --> 00:52:22.640
[Guest 2]: pain to an adversary if it does not act according to our interest, and it should be able to

00:52:22.640 --> 00:52:28.080
[Guest 2]: deliver benefits if it does. So that is how we should look at US and China as well. And

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:34.120
[Guest 2]: so issue by issue, we can decide where we want to be on. So it is called like another

00:52:34.120 --> 00:52:38.520
[Guest 2]: analogy for this is we shouldn't be in anyone's camp, but we can be in different tents at

00:52:38.520 --> 00:52:44.320
[Guest 2]: different times. So you could be on, for example, on climate change, India could have more close

00:52:44.320 --> 00:52:50.520
[Guest 2]: relationship with China. But on certain other things, US is more important for India. So

00:52:50.520 --> 00:52:56.260
[Guest 2]: it requires a balance. We don't need... India is a big enough power to be able to do that.

00:52:56.260 --> 00:53:00.600
[Guest 2]: If you ask this question to a small nation state, it's very tough for them to do any

00:53:00.600 --> 00:53:06.040
[Guest 2]: of this balancing because their own power is less. But because India is a significant

00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:11.000
[Guest 2]: power, and we hope it remains so with growing economic strength, then its ability to do

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:15.760
[Guest 2]: this balancing, be in different tents at different times will improve over time. And it also

00:53:15.760 --> 00:53:20.440
[Amit Varma]: strikes me when you were talking about deterrence against China, it also strikes me that perhaps

00:53:20.440 --> 00:53:27.320
[Amit Varma]: a stronger deterrent than say nuclear bombs is a strong economy, because then their incentives

00:53:27.320 --> 00:53:31.920
[Amit Varma]: because you know, they make so much money from our economy that their incentive is to

00:53:31.920 --> 00:53:37.000
[Amit Varma]: keep us healthy, but that doesn't work for Pakistan. So while we need carrots with China,

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:41.320
[Amit Varma]: perhaps these kind of positive some carrots, we need sticks with Pakistan, would that be

00:53:41.320 --> 00:53:45.320
[Guest 1]: a fair characterization? So I'd say that we need a bit of both with China, we need to

00:53:45.320 --> 00:53:50.000
[Guest 1]: be able to have the capacity and display the resolve to be able to inflict pain, but we

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:55.120
[Guest 1]: need carrots because it is beneficial to us also. And the fact that over the last 60-65

00:53:55.120 --> 00:54:00.200
[Guest 1]: years, we've been able to manage the border tensions without any major incidents, the

00:54:00.200 --> 00:54:04.520
[Guest 1]: Chinese have not sort of protruded inside India, they've not even sought to, there have

00:54:04.520 --> 00:54:07.920
[Guest 1]: been differences, which cause incursions and those sorts of things. But there's nothing

00:54:07.920 --> 00:54:11.800
[Guest 1]: that that's been large scale. And there's nothing that tells us that there will be something,

00:54:11.800 --> 00:54:15.280
[Guest 1]: you know, at a massive scale going forward. Likewise, with India, India has not tried

00:54:15.280 --> 00:54:19.440
[Guest 1]: to push through sort of established lines apart from, I mean, as much as we keep reporting

00:54:19.440 --> 00:54:24.160
[Guest 1]: Chinese border incursions, they do the same thing, Indian border incursions. So that's

00:54:24.160 --> 00:54:27.960
[Guest 1]: a perceptual issue. And that happens. Yes, there's also it's but the fact is that it's

00:54:27.960 --> 00:54:32.480
[Guest 1]: also a pain point for us, which the Chinese tend to leverage also. So it's not just innocent

00:54:32.480 --> 00:54:36.400
[Guest 1]: perception. It's also thought out sort of approach to this. In terms of carrots, yes,

00:54:36.400 --> 00:54:39.480
[Guest 1]: we need carrots. I think this is one place where sort of we in the office tend to have

00:54:39.480 --> 00:54:44.240
[Guest 1]: a discussion about is that can these carrots influence Chinese policy? What evidence has

00:54:44.240 --> 00:54:48.080
[Guest 1]: shown us that in certain cases, it can in certain cases, it won't. So for example, when

00:54:48.080 --> 00:54:52.400
[Guest 1]: the Chinese ended up entering into a sort of conflict with the Japanese, this phase

00:54:52.400 --> 00:54:57.520
[Guest 1]: of tension starting from 2012 onwards, over the disputed islands between the two countries,

00:54:57.520 --> 00:55:03.200
[Guest 1]: you ended up realizing that the Chinese were willing to bear economic costs, whether it

00:55:03.200 --> 00:55:07.120
[Guest 1]: was to Japanese businesses in China, or whether it was sort of dealing with cutting off ties,

00:55:07.120 --> 00:55:10.600
[Guest 1]: sort of restricting hurting Chinese exports and all those sorts of things. They were willing

00:55:10.600 --> 00:55:15.000
[Guest 1]: to deal with economic costs. In the case of the US right now, and sort of tensions between

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:18.280
[Guest 1]: the Americans and the Chinese, what you're seeing is that they're again willing to bear

00:55:18.280 --> 00:55:23.480
[Guest 1]: economic costs for strategic objectives. Yet, when those economic costs start to hurt the

00:55:23.480 --> 00:55:28.000
[Guest 1]: stability of the party, that's when it becomes far more important. So it might not necessarily

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:32.800
[Guest 1]: be a case where a certain large, certain set of large industry sort of lobbies can get

00:55:32.800 --> 00:55:36.720
[Guest 1]: together and influence the government in China, like they could probably in the US or probably

00:55:36.720 --> 00:55:41.640
[Guest 1]: in India, to alter policies, soften policy or do something like that. But when those

00:55:41.640 --> 00:55:47.200
[Guest 1]: industries are critical to survival for the Communist Party, you'll end up seeing them

00:55:47.200 --> 00:55:52.600
[Guest 1]: sort of altering course, it might not just be sort of the profit margins being hurt badly.

00:55:52.600 --> 00:55:56.240
[Guest 1]: So I think that is what we need to keep in mind when we try to take, if our carrots are,

00:55:56.240 --> 00:56:00.640
[Guest 1]: the purpose of the carrots is to sort of try and shift policy over a period of time, it

00:56:00.640 --> 00:56:03.840
[Guest 1]: has to be focused with sort of very clear sort of precision that what are you looking

00:56:03.840 --> 00:56:07.040
[Guest 1]: at, where are you targeting, it might not necessarily be sufficient just because you're

00:56:07.040 --> 00:56:11.000
[Guest 1]: a large enough market where you can, where they are making 100 billion dollars a year,

00:56:11.000 --> 00:56:14.120
[Guest 1]: that might not essentially be sufficient. So there may be a lot more that needs to be

00:56:14.120 --> 00:56:15.120
[Guest 2]: done.

00:56:15.120 --> 00:56:18.720
[Guest 2]: Yeah, I look at it from like an insurance policy, right? You need an insurance when

00:56:18.720 --> 00:56:23.960
[Guest 2]: things go wrong, right? Similarly, I articulate what India's policy towards China should be

00:56:23.960 --> 00:56:29.040
[Guest 2]: in two parts. One is what Manoj said about part one, we need Yogakshema, it's in our

00:56:29.040 --> 00:56:33.320
[Guest 2]: national interest that there are more investments, there is peace on the border. So whatever

00:56:33.320 --> 00:56:37.320
[Guest 2]: requires to be done with China on that we should do, we should allow Chinese investments

00:56:37.320 --> 00:56:42.120
[Guest 2]: in a lot of at least the dump infrastructure in India, definitely a yes, right? But we

00:56:42.120 --> 00:56:47.920
[Guest 2]: also need an aggressive China insurance policy. So what if, because China's recent movements

00:56:47.920 --> 00:56:56.480
[Guest 2]: have been in Maldives, Nepal, Doklam are quite indicative that it is ready to take openly

00:56:56.480 --> 00:57:01.600
[Guest 2]: hostile relationship with its neighbors, not just India, it has been the case with many.

00:57:01.600 --> 00:57:08.480
[Guest 2]: So we need at least some instruments to be able to deliver pain to China if it tries

00:57:08.480 --> 00:57:14.360
[Guest 2]: this, right? So for example, some things, the insurance premium for this policy would

00:57:14.360 --> 00:57:19.920
[Guest 2]: include a variety of measures, for example, establishing at least contacts with key members

00:57:19.920 --> 00:57:24.960
[Guest 2]: of the World Uyghur Congress, for example, because that is a pain point for them. Shifting

00:57:24.960 --> 00:57:30.640
[Guest 2]: the focus of our Act East and Look East policy to just one country, Vietnam, for example,

00:57:30.640 --> 00:57:36.960
[Guest 2]: because it is a country which also has a historic problem with China in its neighborhood. Third,

00:57:36.960 --> 00:57:42.360
[Guest 2]: offering Trump deals that can actually deepen the US-India engagement. And fourth, actually

00:57:42.360 --> 00:57:47.480
[Guest 2]: sponsoring studies that puncture the Chinese leaders do no wrong narrative, because that's

00:57:47.480 --> 00:57:51.520
[Guest 2]: a very strong thing. Everything in China is planned and everything they do is a success.

00:57:51.520 --> 00:57:57.840
[Guest 2]: Dear leader is never wrong, sounds familiar, Indian listeners. So these are just, this

00:57:57.840 --> 00:58:02.200
[Guest 2]: is not a comprehensive list by any means, but these are some things which we can develop

00:58:02.200 --> 00:58:06.160
[Guest 2]: our strength in so that if things go wrong with China, we at least have well-developed,

00:58:06.160 --> 00:58:10.800
[Guest 1]: crafted instruments. Yeah, I think the only, the one thing that I would add to this is,

00:58:10.800 --> 00:58:15.080
[Guest 1]: you know, our relationship with Taiwan. The fact that we've not really been able to leverage

00:58:15.080 --> 00:58:19.320
[Guest 1]: that relationship at all, which apart from just as an insurance policy with regard to

00:58:19.320 --> 00:58:23.080
[Guest 1]: China is also useful from the point of view of our own technological development. Given

00:58:23.080 --> 00:58:26.800
[Guest 1]: that we want to talk about indigenizing semiconductors and all of that, we need to work with the

00:58:26.800 --> 00:58:30.560
[Guest 1]: Japanese. And I don't think we've done enough. I mean, I, we just had elections in Taiwan

00:58:30.560 --> 00:58:34.560
[Guest 1]: and for whom I had put out on social media that it would be nice to see the Indian government

00:58:34.560 --> 00:58:39.480
[Guest 1]: put out a statement saying that, you know, congratulations, well, you know, good elections

00:58:39.480 --> 00:58:44.400
[Guest 1]: and you know, congratulations on peaceful transfer of power and just as generic as that,

00:58:44.400 --> 00:58:47.920
[Guest 1]: without even using the word president side, because we don't recognize Taiwan as a state,

00:58:47.920 --> 00:58:51.120
[Guest 1]: but just congratulating them. When the Australians can, when the Americans can, why can't we?

00:58:51.120 --> 00:58:53.640
[Guest 1]: It might, it will urge the Chinese, of course, it'll urge the Chinese, but it won't take

00:58:53.640 --> 00:58:56.920
[Guest 1]: you for granted. Yeah, they won't take you for granted. So I don't see why we don't do

00:58:56.920 --> 00:59:01.400
[Guest 1]: that and why we've also sort of become far more soft on Tibet. These are complicated

00:59:01.400 --> 00:59:05.640
[Guest 1]: issues for the Chinese that are going to remain complicated for the next, at least for the

00:59:05.640 --> 00:59:08.880
[Guest 1]: next decade plus. Taiwan's going to be there for a longer period of time, but given that

00:59:08.880 --> 00:59:13.240
[Guest 1]: the Dalai Lama is aging and his health hasn't been the best, Tibet's going to be a complicated

00:59:13.240 --> 00:59:16.720
[Guest 1]: issue for the Chinese. I don't know how much we've done to sort of nurture some of these

00:59:16.720 --> 00:59:20.560
[Guest 1]: pain points. I don't think we've done sufficient. In fact, what we've done in the last few years

00:59:20.560 --> 00:59:24.360
[Guest 1]: is that we've actually rolled back some of the pressure that we apply on this. So when

00:59:24.360 --> 00:59:27.760
[Amit Varma]: you say nurture the pain points, you're saying keep it alive as an issue. Yes. So they are

00:59:27.760 --> 00:59:31.760
[Amit Varma]: wary of messing too much with you on other fronts because you could mess with them on

00:59:31.760 --> 00:59:35.100
[Guest 1]: this front, basically. To me, the fact is that the fact that we are no longer even issuing

00:59:35.100 --> 00:59:39.440
[Guest 1]: statements to any regard tells you of the fact that you, I mean, I don't know what capacity

00:59:39.440 --> 00:59:42.840
[Guest 1]: we'd have in Tibet, if we have any, I don't. The fact that we are no longer even talking

00:59:42.840 --> 00:59:46.440
[Guest 1]: about it tells you that we probably have no capacity. If you had some capacity, you would

00:59:46.440 --> 00:59:51.400
[Guest 1]: talk about it because empty talk is otherwise useless. So I presume that we've not nurtured

00:59:51.400 --> 00:59:54.960
[Guest 1]: that capacity. And if you've not done that, therefore we're not talking. So I think we

00:59:54.960 --> 00:59:59.680
[Guest 2]: should be looking to do some of these things. Actually, we're going the other direction,

00:59:59.680 --> 01:00:04.040
[Guest 2]: because Pakistan has become again important for this government. The opportunity cost

01:00:04.040 --> 01:00:08.560
[Guest 2]: of that is that we are not going to be looking at China with such, with all these instruments.

01:00:08.560 --> 01:00:13.000
[Guest 2]: We're not going to develop them. In fact, we are going to need China on our hand to

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:17.920
[Guest 2]: take on Pakistan. And for just the case of that Masood Azhar listing is a classic case

01:00:17.920 --> 01:00:23.520
[Guest 2]: because it is so important to us. We want China's support for that delisting and all

01:00:23.520 --> 01:00:28.880
[Guest 2]: cannot happen. So we are going in the other direction by making Pakistan the focus of

01:00:28.880 --> 01:00:33.560
[Amit Varma]: our foreign policy. And we shall make Pakistan the focus of our conversation after we come

01:00:33.560 --> 01:00:43.560
[Amit Varma]: back commercial break.

